{"title_page": "Virtual Soldier Research Program", "text_new": "The '''Virtual Soldier Research program''' (VSR) is a research group within the [[University of Iowa]]  [[Center for Computer-Aided Design]] (CCAD). VSR was founded by Professor [https://www.engineering.uiowa.edu/faculty-staff/karim-abdel-malek Karim Abdel-Malek] in 2003 through external funding from the US Army Tank Automotive Command (TACOM) to put the Warfighter at the center of US Army product designs.<ref>Abdel-Malek, K., Yang, J., Kim, J.H., Beck, S., Swan, C., Frey-Law, L., Mathai, A., Murphy, C., Rahmatalla, S., and Arora, J. (2007). Development of the Virtual-Human Santos\u2122. In V.G. Duffy (Ed.): Digital Human Modeling, HCII 2007, LNCS-4561, pp. 490-499.\n</ref> [http://user.engineering.uiowa.edu/~amalek/ Professor Abdel-Malek]'s background in robotics and the use of rigorous mathematical formulations was the first introduction of mathematical kinematics to the field of Digital Human Modeling (DHM).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou (James)|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|date=January 2009|title=Human reach envelope and zone differentiation for ergonomic design|journal=Human Factors and Ergonomics in Manufacturing|volume=19|issue=1|pages=15\u201334|doi=10.1002/hfm.20135|issn=1090-8471}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Hyung Joo|last2=Wang|first2=Qian|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Swan|first4=Colby C.|last5=Arora|first5=Jasbir S.|last6=Abdel-Malek|first6=Karim|last7=Assouline|first7=Jose G.|date=2008-04-21|title=Dynamic Motion Planning of 3D Human Locomotion Using Gradient-Based Optimization|journal=Journal of Biomechanical Engineering|volume=130|issue=3|pages=031002|doi=10.1115/1.2898730|pmid=18532851|issn=0148-0731}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mi|first=Zan|last2=Farrell|first2=Kim|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2004-06-15|title=Virtual Environment for Digital Human Simulation|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2004-01-2172}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mi|first=Zan|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou (James)|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=July 2009|title=Optimization-based posture prediction for human upper body|journal=Robotica|volume=27|issue=4|pages=607\u2013620|doi=10.1017/s0263574708004992|issn=0263-5747}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim A.|title=Posture Prediction and Optimization|date=2013|work=Human Motion Simulation|pages=41\u201368|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-405190-4|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir Singh|doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-405190-4.00003-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Ross|last2=Smith|first2=Brian Lewis|last3=Penmatsa|first3=Rajeev|last4=Marler|first4=Tim|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2009-06-09|title=Real-Time Obstacle Avoidance for Posture Prediction|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2009-01-2305}}</ref>  Prior to 2003, all DHM models were based on experimental data that use lookup tables to enable the posturing of simple mannequins. Indeed, the first version of Santos, presented at the a DHM conference was met with great success because it was the first fully articulated digital human model that behaved as humans do,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Yu|first2=Wei|last3=Jaber|first3=Mohamad|last4=Duncan|first4=Jerry|date=2001-06-26|title=Realistic Posture Prediction for Maximum Dexterity|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2001-01-2110}}</ref> whereby joints had constraints (also called ranges of motion) and a user could pull on an arm for example and as a result the entire body would respond accordingly.  Cost functions representing human performance measures were used to drive the motion within the optimization formulation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marler|first=Timothy|last2=Farrell|first2=Kimberly|last3=Kim|first3=Joo|last4=Rahmatalla|first4=Salam|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2006-07-04|title=Vision Performance Measures for Optimization-Based Posture Prediction|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2006-01-2334}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Rahmatalla|first2=Salam|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir S.|last4=Malek|first4=Karim Abdel|date=2011|title=Enhanced optimisation-based inverse kinematics methodology considering joint discomfort|journal=International Journal of Human Factors Modelling and Simulation|volume=2|issue=1/2|pages=111|doi=10.1504/ijhfms.2011.041640|issn=1742-5549}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Yu|first2=Wei|last3=Jaber|first3=Mohamad|last4=Duncan|first4=Jerry|date=2001-06-26|title=Realistic Posture Prediction for Maximum Dexterity|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2001-01-2110}}</ref> Seated posture prediction for example was accomplished by simply providing the seat geometry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou (James)|last3=Malek|first3=Karim Abdel|date=2009|title=Multi-objective optimisation approach for predicting seated posture considering balance|journal=International Journal of Vehicle Design|volume=51|issue=3/4|pages=278|doi=10.1504/ijvd.2009.027957|issn=0143-3369}}</ref> The posture prediction methodology was subsequently validated<ref>{{Citation|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|chapter=Validation of Predicted Posture for the Virtual Human SantosTM|pages=500\u2013510|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-540-73318-8|last2=Rahmatalla|first2=Salam|last3=Marler|first3=Tim|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|last5=Harrison|first5=Chad|title=Digital Human Modeling|volume=4561|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-73321-8_58|series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science|year=2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marler|first=Timothy|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|last5=Harrison|first5=Chad|date=2007-06-12|title=Validation Methodology Development for Predicted Posture|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2007-01-2467}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rahmatalla|first=Salam|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Smith|first3=Rosalind|last4=Li|first4=Jinzheng|last5=Muesch|first5=John|last6=Bhatt|first6=Rajan|last7=Swan|first7=Colby|last8=Arora|first8=Jasbir S.|last9=Abdel-Malek|first9=Karim|date=2008-06-17|title=A Validation Protocol for Predictive Human Locomotion|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2008-01-1855}}</ref>  Later on, the Predictive Dynamics method was created and used the same optimization technique with the addition of 3D laws of motion (equations of motion).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hyun-Joon|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Xiang|first4=Yujiang|date=2015-03-01|title=Dynamic Optimization of Human Running With Analytical Gradients|journal=Journal of Computational and Nonlinear Dynamics|volume=10|issue=2|doi=10.1115/1.4027672|issn=1555-1415}}</ref>  The Santos system includes many aspects of physiology modeling,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Farrell|first4=Kimberly|last5=Nebel|first5=Kyle|date=2005-06-14|title=Optimization-Based Dynamic Motion Simulation and Energy Expenditure Prediction for a Digital Human|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2717}}</ref> thermal, hand model,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pitarch|first=Esteban Pe\u00f1a|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2005-06-14|title=SANTOS\u2122 Hand: A 25 Degree-of-Freedom Model|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2727}}</ref> grasp prediction,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Goussous|first=F.|last2=Marler|first2=T.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=K.|date=March 2009|title=A New Methodology for Human Grasp Prediction|journal=IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics - Part A: Systems and Humans|volume=39|issue=2|pages=369\u2013380|doi=10.1109/tsmca.2008.2010090|issn=1083-4427}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Pe\u00f1a-Pitarch|first=Esteban|title=Virtual Human Hand: Grasping and Simulation|date=2009|work=Digital Human Modeling|pages=140\u2013149|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-642-02808-3|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-02809-0_16}}</ref> gait analysis including stability,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Bhatt|first3=Rajankumar|last4=Yang|first4=Jingzhou|last5=Chung|first5=Hyun-Joon|last6=Patrick|first6=Amos|last7=Arora|first7=Jasbir S.|last8=Abdel-Malek|first8=Karim|date=2008-01-01|title=Efficient ZMP Formulation and Effective Whole-Body Motion Generation for a Human-Like Mechanism|journal=Volume 2: 32nd Mechanisms and Robotics Conference, Parts a and B|pages=1073\u20131084|publisher=ASMEDC|doi=10.1115/detc2008-49925|isbn=978-0-7918-4326-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hyun-Joon|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Xiang|first4=Yujiang|date=2015-03-01|title=Dynamic Optimization of Human Running With Analytical Gradients|journal=Journal of Computational and Nonlinear Dynamics|volume=10|issue=2|doi=10.1115/1.4027672|issn=1555-1415}}</ref> mobility, suitability, survivability, maintainability, training,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defensesystems.com/articles/2012/06/04/virtual-soldier-research-future-troops.aspx|title=Virtual soldier brings military training into the real world -|last=Corrin|first=By Amber|last2=Jun 05|first2=2012|website=Defense Systems|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> and many other metrics typically used in the assessment of human performance for the Warfighter.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hariri|first=Mahdiar|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2012-08-12|title=Optimization-Based Prediction of Aiming and Kneeling Military Tasks Performed by a Soldier|journal=Volume 3: 38th Design Automation Conference, Parts a and B|pages=661\u2013671|publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers|doi=10.1115/detc2012-71166|isbn=978-0-7918-4502-8}}</ref>\n\nUsing this initial research and funding as a foundation, the VSR program continues to develop new technologies in digital human modeling and simulation, specifically with applications for the military, automotive, manufacturing, athletics, injury prediction, With over $60M in funding, the Santos simulation platform provides two key components that differentiates it among all other DHM systems: (1) Physics based<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.press-citizen.com/story/news/education/university-of-iowa/2016/02/15/uis-virtual-solider-program-help-prevent-injuries/80423478/|title=UI's virtual soldier program to help prevent injuries|last=Charis-Carlson|first=Jeff|website=Iowa City Press-Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> and (2) Predicts behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrg.com/content/news/UI-Engineering-department-sees-progress-in-virtual-soldier-predicting-injuries-475022863.html|title=UI Engineering department sees progress in virtual soldier, predicting injuries|last=Navarro (KCRG-TV9)|first=Chantelle|website=www.kcrg.com|language=english|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nVSR's digital human model, Santos (R), stands at the center of its digital human modeling and simulation research.<ref>https://www.ccad.uiowa.edu/vsr/about</ref> The high-fidelity, biomechanically and biofidelic accurate musculoskeletal model incorporates 215 [[degrees of freedom]], including the hand,<ref>Pena-Pitarch, E., Yang, J., and Abdel-Malek, K. (2005). Santos\u2122 Hand: A 25-Degree-of-Freedom Model, SAE Technical Paper 2005-01-2727, {{doi|10.4271/2005-01-2727}}.</ref> feet, and eyes. The dimensions of the skeleton are mutable, able to represent any anthropometric cross section. In addition, Santos includes a muscular system with the ability to predict muscle activation and muscle forces in real time, using a novel optimization-based methodology.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marler|first=R. Timothy|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Kim|first4=Hyung-Joo|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2009-09-18|title=Use of multi-objective optimization for digital human posture prediction|journal=Engineering Optimization|volume=41|issue=10|pages=925\u2013943|doi=10.1080/03052150902853013|issn=0305-215X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Mi|first2=Zan|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=2006-07-03|title=Optimization-based trajectory planning of the human upper body|journal=Robotica|volume=24|issue=6|pages=683\u2013696|doi=10.1017/s0263574706002852|issn=0263-5747}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Marler|first2=R. Timothy|last3=Beck|first3=Steven|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|last5=Kim|first5=Joo|date=March 2006|title=Real-Time Optimal Reach-Posture Prediction in a New Interactive Virtual Environment|journal=Journal of Computer Science and Technology|volume=21|issue=2|pages=189\u2013198|doi=10.1007/s11390-006-0189-3|issn=1000-9000}}</ref> This method, developed over a period of eight years by the Virtual Soldier Research program is called Predictive Dynamics and published by a book<ref>{{Cite book|title=Human motion simulation : predictive dynamics|last=Abdel-Malek, Karim|others=Arora, Jasbir S.|isbn=978-0-12-404601-6|location=Waltham, MA|oclc=847948857|date = 2013-05-30}}</ref> and a large number of papers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2010-03-18|title=Physics-based modeling and simulation of human walking: a review of optimization-based and other approaches|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=42|issue=1|pages=1\u201323|doi=10.1007/s00158-010-0496-8|issn=1615-147X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Chung|first2=Hyun-Joon|last3=Kim|first3=Joo H.|last4=Bhatt|first4=Rajankumar|last5=Rahmatalla|first5=Salam|last6=Yang|first6=Jingzhou|last7=Marler|first7=Timothy|last8=Arora|first8=Jasbir S.|last9=Abdel-Malek|first9=Karim|date=2009-08-21|title=Predictive dynamics: an optimization-based novel approach for human motion simulation|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=41|issue=3|pages=465\u2013479|doi=10.1007/s00158-009-0423-z|issn=1615-147X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|date=2009-08-06|title=Optimization-based dynamic human walking prediction: One step formulation|journal=International Journal for Numerical Methods in Engineering|volume=79|issue=6|pages=667\u2013695|doi=10.1002/nme.2575|bibcode=2009IJNME..79..667X|issn=0029-5981}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Chung|first3=Hyun-Joon|last4=Kwon|first4=Hyun-Jung|last5=Rahmatalla|first5=Salam|last6=Bhatt|first6=Rajankumar|last7=Abdel-Malek|first7=Karim|date=2011-09-27|title=Predictive simulation of human walking transitions using an optimization formulation|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=45|issue=5|pages=759\u2013772|doi=10.1007/s00158-011-0712-1|issn=1615-147X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2008-01-10|title=A novel formulation for determining joint constraint loads during optimal dynamic motion of redundant manipulators in DH representation|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=19|issue=4|pages=427\u2013451|doi=10.1007/s11044-007-9100-4|issn=1384-5640}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|title=Physics-Based Digital Human Modeling|date=2008-11-20|work=Human Factors and Ergonomics|pages=5\u20131\u20135\u201333|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8058-5646-0|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|doi=10.1201/9781420063523.ch5}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim A.|title=Posture Prediction and Optimization|date=2013|work=Human Motion Simulation|pages=41\u201368|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-405190-4|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir Singh|doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-405190-4.00003-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=XIANG|first=YUJIANG|last2=ARORA|first2=JASBIR S.|last3=ABDEL-MALEK|first3=KARIM|title=3D Human Lifting Motion Prediction with Different Performance Measures|date=June 2012|journal=International Journal of Humanoid Robotics|volume=09|issue=2|pages=1250012|doi=10.1142/s0219843612500120|issn=0219-8436}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Nebel|first5=Kyle|date=2005-01-01|title=Lifting Posture Analysis in Material Handling Using Virtual Humans|journal=Manufacturing Engineering and Materials Handling, Parts a and B|pages=1445\u20131453|publisher=ASMEDC|doi=10.1115/imece2005-81801|isbn=0-7918-4223-1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hariri|first=Mahdiar|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Chung|first3=Hyun-Joon|last4=Bhatt|first4=Rajan|last5=Arora|first5=Jasbir|last6=Abdel-Malek|first6=Karim|date=2013-10-21|title=Simulation and Prediction of the Motion of a Human in a Vertical Jumping Task|journal=Volume 1: Aerial Vehicles; Aerospace Control; Alternative Energy; Automotive Control Systems; Battery Systems; Beams and Flexible Structures; Biologically-Inspired Control and Its Applications; Bio-Medical and Bio-Mechanical Systems; Biomedical Robots and Rehab; Bipeds and Locomotion; Control Design Methods for Adv. Powertrain Systems and Components; Control of Adv. Combustion Engines, Building Energy Systems, Mechanical Systems; Control, Monitoring, and Energy Harvesting of Vibratory Systems|publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers|doi=10.1115/dscc2013-4091|isbn=978-0-7918-5612-3}}</ref>   Furthermore, the gradient based methodology used to solve for the motion was also replaced with an artificial intelligence neural network method.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bataineh|first=Mohammad|last2=Marler|first2=Timothy|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Arora|first4=Jasbir|date=April 2016|title=Neural network for dynamic human motion prediction|journal=Expert Systems with Applications|volume=48|pages=26\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.eswa.2015.11.020|issn=0957-4174|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bataineh|first=Mohammad|title=Artificial Neural Network-Based Prediction of Human Posture|date=2013|work=Digital Human Modeling and Applications in Health, Safety, Ergonomics, and Risk Management. Human Body Modeling and Ergonomics|pages=305\u2013313|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-642-39181-1|last2=Marler|first2=Timothy|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-39182-8_36}}</ref>\n\nThe mathematical model for the Santos skeleton was developed based on the [[Denavit\u2013Hartenberg parameters|Denavit-Hartenberg]] method for kinematic and dynamic analysis.<ref>Denavit, J., & Hartenberg, R. S. (1955). A kinematic notation for lower-pair mechanisms based on matrices. Journal of Applied Mechanics,\n77, 215\u2013221.</ref> Optimization is used to determine postures and motions that are governed by various human performance measures (objective functions) and constrained by the restrictions imposed by the skeleton, the laws of physics, and the environment. The Santos simulation platform is being used by the US Military, industry (for example automotive industry),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Kim|first2=Joo H.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Beck|first5=Steven|last6=Kopp|first6=Gregory R.|date=July 2007|title=A new digital human environment and assessment of vehicle interior design|journal=Computer-Aided Design|volume=39|issue=7|pages=548\u2013558|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2006.11.007|issn=0010-4485}}</ref> and academia.  The Virtual Soldier Research team transitioned a product from the Santos environment called Enhanced Technologies for the Optimization of Warfighter Load (ETOWL) funded by the Office of Naval Research (ONR) to the US Marines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://popularmilitary.com/gruntsim-the-marines-new-infantry-simulator/|title=GruntSim, the Marines' new infantry simulator|website=popularmilitary.com|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The product was later renamed as GruntSim.<ref>{{Citation|title=GruntSim is a US Marines simulation for lightening the load, warfighter load, Predictive Dynamic|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RC8hseUmZDw|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>   This human modeling and simulation environment is now being used to  study human factors<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Yu|first2=Wei|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=November 2004|title=A mathematical method for ergonomic-based design: placement|journal=International Journal of Industrial Ergonomics|volume=34|issue=5|pages=375\u2013394|doi=10.1016/j.ergon.2004.05.001|issn=0169-8141}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=DEPARTMENT OF THE ARMY WASHINGTON DC|date=1987-05-08|title=Administration: Civilian Aides to the Secretary of the Army|location=Fort Belvoir, VA|doi=10.21236/ada401816}}</ref> and ergonomics<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Mi|first3=Zan|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=2004-06-15|title=Layout Design using an Optimization-Based Human Energy Consumption Formulation|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2004-01-2175}}</ref> in many applications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Bhatt|first5=Rajankumar|last6=Abdel-Malek|first6=Karim|date=2010-01-21|title=Human lifting simulation using a multi-objective optimization approach|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=23|issue=4|pages=431\u2013451|doi=10.1007/s11044-009-9186-y|issn=1384-5640}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Arora|first4=Jasbir S.|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2010-03-31|title=Dynamic motion planning of overarm throw for a biped human multibody system|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=24|issue=1|pages=1\u201324|doi=10.1007/s11044-010-9193-z|issn=1384-5640}}</ref>  This model includes not only Predictive Dynamics but also stability criteria called Zero Moment Point.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=J.H.|last2=Xiang|first2=Y.|last3=Bhatt|first3=R.M.|last4=Yang|first4=J.|last5=Chung|first5=H.-J.|last6=Arora|first6=J.S.|last7=Abdel-Malek|first7=K.|title=Generating Effective Whole-Body Motions of a Human-Like Mechanism with Efficient ZMP Formulation|date=2009|journal=International Journal of Robotics and Automation|volume=24|issue=2|doi=10.2316/journal.206.2009.2.206-3235|issn=1925-7090}}</ref>  The use of the Santos Digital Human Model for example in assessing assembly issues in the design stage have been demonstrated<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Pitarch|first2=Esteban Pena|last3=Kim|first3=Joo|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|date=2006-07-04|title=Posture Prediction and Force/Torque Analysis for Human Hands|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2006-01-2326}}</ref> and for gait prediction as well.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Hyung Joo|last2=Horn|first2=Emily|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir S.|last4=Malek|first4=Karim Abdel-|date=2005-06-14|title=An Optimization-Based Methodology to Predict Digital Human Gait Motion|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2710}}</ref>  Running for example,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Qian|last2=Xiang|first2=Yu-Jiang|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir|last4=Abdel- Malek|first4=Karim|date=2007-04-23|title=Alternative Formulations for Optimization-Based Human Gait Planning|journal=48th AIAA/ASME/ASCE/AHS/ASC Structures, Structural Dynamics, and Materials Conference|location=Reston, Virigina|publisher=American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics|doi=10.2514/6.2007-1909|isbn=978-1-62410-013-0}}</ref> which substantially more difficult to predict for a virtual human, was accomplished.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hyun-Joon|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Mathai|first3=Anith|last4=Rahmatalla|first4=Salam|last5=Kim|first5=Joo|last6=Marler|first6=Timothy|last7=Beck|first7=Steve|last8=Yang|first8=Jingzhou|last9=Arora|first9=Jasbir|last10=Abdel-Malek|first10=Karim|last11=Obusek|first11=John|date=2007-06-12|title=A Robust Formulation for Prediction of Human Running|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2007-01-2490}}</ref>\n\nThe Santos simulation platform was developed from the ground up.  Using the 215 DOF and based on the use of optimization based methods that enable cost functions to drive the motion, the numerical algorithm drives the motion to predict joint variables across time (also called joint profiles) and subject to a number of constraints.  For example, predicting gait of any body type is now possible.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=April 2011|title=Erratum to \"Optimization-based prediction of asymmetric human gait\" [J. Biomech. 44 (4) (2011) 683\u2013693]|journal=Journal of Biomechanics|volume=44|issue=6|pages=1217|doi=10.1016/j.jbiomech.2011.02.080|issn=0021-9290}}</ref>  Similarly, any task can be modeled and simulated using this approach.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Malek|first2=Karim Abdel|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Marler|first4=R. Timothy|date=2006|title=Prediction and analysis of human motion dynamics performing various tasks|journal=International Journal of Human Factors Modelling and Simulation|volume=1|issue=1|pages=69|doi=10.1504/ijhfms.2006.011683|issn=1742-5549}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2008-05-14|title=Optimization-based motion prediction of mechanical systems: sensitivity analysis|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=37|issue=6|pages=595\u2013608|doi=10.1007/s00158-008-0247-2|issn=1615-147X}}</ref> Xiang, Yujiang, Jasbir S. Arora, and Karim Abdel-Malek. \"Hybrid predictive dynamics: a new approach to simulate human motion.\" ''Multibody System Dynamics'' 28.3 (2012): 199-224.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2012-03-28|title=Hybrid predictive dynamics: a new approach to simulate human motion|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=28|issue=3|pages=199\u2013224|doi=10.1007/s11044-012-9306-y|issn=1384-5640}}</ref>\n\nThe Santos system was also used to predict injury for various activities, particularly musculoskeletal injuries in atheltics, military, manufacturing, and other domains.<ref>{{Citation|last=Sultan|first=Sultan|title=An Integrated Computational Simulation System for Injury Assessment|date=2016-07-06|work=Advances in Intelligent Systems and Computing|pages=23\u201334|publisher=Springer International Publishing|isbn=978-3-319-41626-7|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir|last4=Bhatt|first4=Rajan|last5=Marler|first5=Tim|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-41627-4_3}}</ref>\n\nVSR research has led to the spin-off of a private company, Santos Human Inc.,<ref>http://www.santoshumaninc.com/</ref> specifically focused on product development.\n\n'''Who is Santos\u2122?'''\n\nSantos is the only physics-based<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Beck|first5=Steve|last6=Swan|first6=Colby|last7=Frey-Law|first7=Laura|last8=Mathai|first8=Anith|last9=Murphy|first9=Chris|last10=Rahmatallah|first10=Salam|last11=Patrick|first11=Amos|date=October 2006|title=Santos: A Physics-Based Digital Human Simulation Environment|journal=Proceedings of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society Annual Meeting|volume=50|issue=20|pages=2279\u20132283|doi=10.1177/154193120605002009|issn=1541-9312}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Malek|first=Karim Abdel|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou (James)|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Beck|first5=Steve|last6=Swan|first6=Colby|last7=Law|first7=Laura Frey|last8=Kim|first8=Joo|last9=Bhatt|first9=Rajan|last10=Mathai|first10=Anith|last11=Murphy|first11=Chris|date=2009|title=A physics-based digital human model|journal=International Journal of Vehicle Design|volume=51|issue=3/4|pages=324|doi=10.1504/ijvd.2009.027960|issn=0143-3369}}</ref> virtual human that stands at the center of the digital human modeling and simulation research at the University of Iowa and in use by the US Army and the US Marines. This high-fidelity, biofidelic, biomechanically and physiologically accurate musculoskeletal model was developed from the inside out by a large multidisciplinary team, and incorporates 215 degrees of freedom, including the hand, feet, and eyes. The dimensions of the skeleton are mutable, able to represent any anthropometric cross section. In addition, Santos includes a muscular system with the ability to predict muscle activation and muscle forces in real time, using a novel optimization-based methodology.  The Santos system has been used in many applications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|date=July 2007|title=Human modeling and applications special issue|journal=Computer-Aided Design|volume=39|issue=7|pages=539|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2007.04.001|issn=0010-4485}}</ref>\n\nOver time, the Santos family has grown to incorporate a variety of different body scans to provide a range of models that include our female version, Sophia, and a broad array of different body shapes, types, and sizes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Marler|first2=Tim|last3=Kim|first3=HyungJoo|last4=Farrell|first4=Kimberly|last5=Mathai|first5=Anith|last6=Beck|first6=Steven|last7=Abdel-Malek|first7=Karim|last8=Arora|first8=Jasbir|last9=Nebel|first9=Kyle|date=2005-04-11|title=Santos\u2122: A New Generation of Virtual Humans|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-1407}}</ref> Our research is currently being extended to allow multiple digital human models to interact with each other to complete tasks cooperatively.\n\nSantos was built using state-of-the-art technologies adapted from robotics, Hollywood, and the game industry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Farrell|first3=Kim|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=2004-01-01|title=The Iowa Interactive Digital-Human Virtual Environment|journal=Manufacturing Engineering and Materials Handling Engineering|pages=1059\u20131067|publisher=ASMEDC|doi=10.1115/imece2004-61791|isbn=0-7918-4713-6}}</ref> VSR research continues to grow in its dynamic capabilities, physiology, and intelligent behaviors through integration of Artificial Intelligence, design optimization, physics-based modeling, and advanced, multi-scale physiological models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Farrell|first4=Kimberly|last5=Nebel|first5=Kyle|date=2005-06-14|title=Optimization-Based Dynamic Motion Simulation and Energy Expenditure Prediction for a Digital Human|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2717}}</ref>\n\nThe mathematical model for the Santos skeleton was developed based on the Denavit-Hartenberg method for kinematic and dynamic analysis. Optimization is used to determine postures and motions that are governed by various human performance measures (objective functions) and constrained by the restrictions imposed by the skeleton, the laws of physics, and the environment. The software must be as fast and efficient as possible in an effort to provide real-time simulations.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n<!-- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n[[Category:Anatomical simulation]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Virtual Soldier Research program''' (VSR) is a research group within the [[University of Iowa]]  [[Center for Computer-Aided Design]] (CCAD). VSR was founded by Professor [https://www.engineering.uiowa.edu/faculty-staff/karim-abdel-malek Karim Abdel-Malek] in 2003 through external funding from the US Army Tank Automotive Command (TACOM) to put the Warfighter at the center of US Army product designs.<ref>Abdel-Malek, K., Yang, J., Kim, J.H., Beck, S., Swan, C., Frey-Law, L., Mathai, A., Murphy, C., Rahmatalla, S., and Arora, J. (2007). Development of the Virtual-Human Santos\u2122. In V.G. Duffy (Ed.): Digital Human Modeling, HCII 2007, LNCS-4561, pp. 490-499.\n</ref> [http://user.engineering.uiowa.edu/~amalek/ Professor Abdel-Malek]'s background in robotics and the use of rigorous mathematical formulations was the first introduction of mathematical kinematics to the field of Digital Human Modeling (DHM).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou (James)|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|date=January 2009|title=Human reach envelope and zone differentiation for ergonomic design|journal=Human Factors and Ergonomics in Manufacturing|volume=19|issue=1|pages=15\u201334|doi=10.1002/hfm.20135|issn=1090-8471}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Hyung Joo|last2=Wang|first2=Qian|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Swan|first4=Colby C.|last5=Arora|first5=Jasbir S.|last6=Abdel-Malek|first6=Karim|last7=Assouline|first7=Jose G.|date=2008-04-21|title=Dynamic Motion Planning of 3D Human Locomotion Using Gradient-Based Optimization|journal=Journal of Biomechanical Engineering|volume=130|issue=3|pages=031002|doi=10.1115/1.2898730|pmid=18532851|issn=0148-0731}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mi|first=Zan|last2=Farrell|first2=Kim|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2004-06-15|title=Virtual Environment for Digital Human Simulation|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2004-01-2172}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mi|first=Zan|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou (James)|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=July 2009|title=Optimization-based posture prediction for human upper body|journal=Robotica|volume=27|issue=4|pages=607\u2013620|doi=10.1017/s0263574708004992|issn=0263-5747}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim A.|title=Posture Prediction and Optimization|date=2013|work=Human Motion Simulation|pages=41\u201368|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-405190-4|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir Singh|doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-405190-4.00003-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Ross|last2=Smith|first2=Brian Lewis|last3=Penmatsa|first3=Rajeev|last4=Marler|first4=Tim|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2009-06-09|title=Real-Time Obstacle Avoidance for Posture Prediction|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2009-01-2305}}</ref>  Prior to 2003, all DHM models were based on experimental data that use lookup tables to enable the posturing of simple mannequins. Indeed, the first version of Santos, presented at the a DHM conference was met with great success because it was the first fully articulated digital human model that behaved as humans do,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Yu|first2=Wei|last3=Jaber|first3=Mohamad|last4=Duncan|first4=Jerry|date=2001-06-26|title=Realistic Posture Prediction for Maximum Dexterity|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2001-01-2110}}</ref> whereby joints had constraints (also called ranges of motion) and a user could pull on an arm for example and as a result the entire body would respond accordingly.  Cost functions representing human performance measures were used to drive the motion within the optimization formulation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marler|first=Timothy|last2=Farrell|first2=Kimberly|last3=Kim|first3=Joo|last4=Rahmatalla|first4=Salam|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2006-07-04|title=Vision Performance Measures for Optimization-Based Posture Prediction|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2006-01-2334}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Rahmatalla|first2=Salam|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir S.|last4=Malek|first4=Karim Abdel|date=2011|title=Enhanced optimisation-based inverse kinematics methodology considering joint discomfort|journal=International Journal of Human Factors Modelling and Simulation|volume=2|issue=1/2|pages=111|doi=10.1504/ijhfms.2011.041640|issn=1742-5549}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Yu|first2=Wei|last3=Jaber|first3=Mohamad|last4=Duncan|first4=Jerry|date=2001-06-26|title=Realistic Posture Prediction for Maximum Dexterity|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2001-01-2110}}</ref> Seated posture prediction for example was accomplished by simply providing the seat geometry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou (James)|last3=Malek|first3=Karim Abdel|date=2009|title=Multi-objective optimisation approach for predicting seated posture considering balance|journal=International Journal of Vehicle Design|volume=51|issue=3/4|pages=278|doi=10.1504/ijvd.2009.027957|issn=0143-3369}}</ref> The posture prediction methodology was subsequently validated<ref>{{Citation|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|chapter=Validation of Predicted Posture for the Virtual Human SantosTM|pages=500\u2013510|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-540-73318-8|last2=Rahmatalla|first2=Salam|last3=Marler|first3=Tim|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|last5=Harrison|first5=Chad|title=Digital Human Modeling|volume=4561|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-73321-8_58|series=Lecture Notes in Computer Science|year=2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marler|first=Timothy|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|last5=Harrison|first5=Chad|date=2007-06-12|title=Validation Methodology Development for Predicted Posture|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2007-01-2467}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rahmatalla|first=Salam|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Smith|first3=Rosalind|last4=Li|first4=Jinzheng|last5=Muesch|first5=John|last6=Bhatt|first6=Rajan|last7=Swan|first7=Colby|last8=Arora|first8=Jasbir S.|last9=Abdel-Malek|first9=Karim|date=2008-06-17|title=A Validation Protocol for Predictive Human Locomotion|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2008-01-1855}}</ref>  Later on, the Predictive Dynamics method was created and used the same optimization technique with the addition of 3D laws of motion (equations of motion).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hyun-Joon|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Xiang|first4=Yujiang|date=2015-03-01|title=Dynamic Optimization of Human Running With Analytical Gradients|journal=Journal of Computational and Nonlinear Dynamics|volume=10|issue=2|doi=10.1115/1.4027672|issn=1555-1415}}</ref>  The Santos system includes many aspects of physiology modeling,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Farrell|first4=Kimberly|last5=Nebel|first5=Kyle|date=2005-06-14|title=Optimization-Based Dynamic Motion Simulation and Energy Expenditure Prediction for a Digital Human|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2717}}</ref> thermal, hand model,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pitarch|first=Esteban Pe\u00f1a|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2005-06-14|title=SANTOS\u2122 Hand: A 25 Degree-of-Freedom Model|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2727}}</ref> grasp prediction,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Goussous|first=F.|last2=Marler|first2=T.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=K.|date=March 2009|title=A New Methodology for Human Grasp Prediction|journal=IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics - Part A: Systems and Humans|volume=39|issue=2|pages=369\u2013380|doi=10.1109/tsmca.2008.2010090|issn=1083-4427}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Pe\u00f1a-Pitarch|first=Esteban|title=Virtual Human Hand: Grasping and Simulation|date=2009|work=Digital Human Modeling|pages=140\u2013149|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-642-02808-3|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-02809-0_16}}</ref> gait analysis including stability,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Bhatt|first3=Rajankumar|last4=Yang|first4=Jingzhou|last5=Chung|first5=Hyun-Joon|last6=Patrick|first6=Amos|last7=Arora|first7=Jasbir S.|last8=Abdel-Malek|first8=Karim|date=2008-01-01|title=Efficient ZMP Formulation and Effective Whole-Body Motion Generation for a Human-Like Mechanism|journal=Volume 2: 32nd Mechanisms and Robotics Conference, Parts a and B|pages=1073\u20131084|publisher=ASMEDC|doi=10.1115/detc2008-49925|isbn=978-0-7918-4326-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hyun-Joon|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Xiang|first4=Yujiang|date=2015-03-01|title=Dynamic Optimization of Human Running With Analytical Gradients|journal=Journal of Computational and Nonlinear Dynamics|volume=10|issue=2|doi=10.1115/1.4027672|issn=1555-1415}}</ref> mobility, suitability, survivability, maintainability, training,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defensesystems.com/articles/2012/06/04/virtual-soldier-research-future-troops.aspx|title=Virtual soldier brings military training into the real world -|last=Corrin|first=By Amber|last2=Jun 05|first2=2012|website=Defense Systems|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> and many other metrics typically used in the assessment of human performance for the Warfighter.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hariri|first=Mahdiar|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2012-08-12|title=Optimization-Based Prediction of Aiming and Kneeling Military Tasks Performed by a Soldier|journal=Volume 3: 38th Design Automation Conference, Parts a and B|pages=661\u2013671|publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers|doi=10.1115/detc2012-71166|isbn=978-0-7918-4502-8}}</ref>\n\nUsing this initial research and funding as a foundation, the VSR program continues to develop new technologies in digital human modeling and simulation, specifically with applications for the military, automotive, manufacturing, athletics, injury prediction, With over $60M in funding, the Santos simulation platform provides two key components that differentiates it among all other DHM systems: (1) Physics based<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.press-citizen.com/story/news/education/university-of-iowa/2016/02/15/uis-virtual-solider-program-help-prevent-injuries/80423478/|title=UI's virtual soldier program to help prevent injuries|last=Charis-Carlson|first=Jeff|website=Iowa City Press-Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> and (2) Predicts behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrg.com/content/news/UI-Engineering-department-sees-progress-in-virtual-soldier-predicting-injuries-475022863.html|title=UI Engineering department sees progress in virtual soldier, predicting injuries|last=Navarro (KCRG-TV9)|first=Chantelle|website=www.kcrg.com|language=english|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nVSR's digital human model, Santos (R), stands at the center of its digital human modeling and simulation research.<ref>https://www.ccad.uiowa.edu/vsr/about</ref> The high-fidelity, biomechanically and biofidelic accurate musculoskeletal model incorporates 215 [[degrees of freedom]], including the hand,<ref>Pena-Pitarch, E., Yang, J., and Abdel-Malek, K. (2005). Santos\u2122 Hand: A 25-Degree-of-Freedom Model, SAE Technical Paper 2005-01-2727, {{doi|10.4271/2005-01-2727}}.</ref> feet, and eyes. The dimensions of the skeleton are mutable, able to represent any anthropometric cross section. In addition, Santos includes a muscular system with the ability to predict muscle activation and muscle forces in real time, using a novel optimization-based methodology.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marler|first=R. Timothy|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Kim|first4=Hyung-Joo|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2009-09-18|title=Use of multi-objective optimization for digital human posture prediction|journal=Engineering Optimization|volume=41|issue=10|pages=925\u2013943|doi=10.1080/03052150902853013|issn=0305-215X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Mi|first2=Zan|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=2006-07-03|title=Optimization-based trajectory planning of the human upper body|journal=Robotica|volume=24|issue=6|pages=683\u2013696|doi=10.1017/s0263574706002852|issn=0263-5747}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Marler|first2=R. Timothy|last3=Beck|first3=Steven|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|last5=Kim|first5=Joo|date=March 2006|title=Real-Time Optimal Reach-Posture Prediction in a New Interactive Virtual Environment|journal=Journal of Computer Science and Technology|volume=21|issue=2|pages=189\u2013198|doi=10.1007/s11390-006-0189-3|issn=1000-9000}}</ref> This method, developed over a period of eight years by the Virtual Soldier Research program is called Predictive Dynamics and published by a book<ref>{{Cite book|title=Human motion simulation : predictive dynamics|last=Abdel-Malek, Karim|others=Arora, Jasbir S.|isbn=978-0-12-404601-6|location=Waltham, MA|oclc=847948857|date = 2013-05-30}}</ref> and a large number of papers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2010-03-18|title=Physics-based modeling and simulation of human walking: a review of optimization-based and other approaches|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=42|issue=1|pages=1\u201323|doi=10.1007/s00158-010-0496-8|issn=1615-147X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Chung|first2=Hyun-Joon|last3=Kim|first3=Joo H.|last4=Bhatt|first4=Rajankumar|last5=Rahmatalla|first5=Salam|last6=Yang|first6=Jingzhou|last7=Marler|first7=Timothy|last8=Arora|first8=Jasbir S.|last9=Abdel-Malek|first9=Karim|date=2009-08-21|title=Predictive dynamics: an optimization-based novel approach for human motion simulation|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=41|issue=3|pages=465\u2013479|doi=10.1007/s00158-009-0423-z|issn=1615-147X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|date=2009-08-06|title=Optimization-based dynamic human walking prediction: One step formulation|journal=International Journal for Numerical Methods in Engineering|volume=79|issue=6|pages=667\u2013695|doi=10.1002/nme.2575|bibcode=2009IJNME..79..667X|issn=0029-5981}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Chung|first3=Hyun-Joon|last4=Kwon|first4=Hyun-Jung|last5=Rahmatalla|first5=Salam|last6=Bhatt|first6=Rajankumar|last7=Abdel-Malek|first7=Karim|date=2011-09-27|title=Predictive simulation of human walking transitions using an optimization formulation|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=45|issue=5|pages=759\u2013772|doi=10.1007/s00158-011-0712-1|issn=1615-147X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Yang|first2=Jingzhou|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2008-01-10|title=A novel formulation for determining joint constraint loads during optimal dynamic motion of redundant manipulators in DH representation|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=19|issue=4|pages=427\u2013451|doi=10.1007/s11044-007-9100-4|issn=1384-5640}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|title=Physics-Based Digital Human Modeling|date=2008-11-20|work=Human Factors and Ergonomics|pages=5\u20131\u20135\u201333|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8058-5646-0|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|doi=10.1201/9781420063523.ch5}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim A.|title=Posture Prediction and Optimization|date=2013|work=Human Motion Simulation|pages=41\u201368|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-405190-4|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir Singh|doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-405190-4.00003-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=XIANG|first=YUJIANG|last2=ARORA|first2=JASBIR S.|last3=ABDEL-MALEK|first3=KARIM|title=3D Human Lifting Motion Prediction with Different Performance Measures|date=June 2012|journal=International Journal of Humanoid Robotics|volume=09|issue=2|pages=1250012|doi=10.1142/s0219843612500120|issn=0219-8436}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Nebel|first5=Kyle|date=2005-01-01|title=Lifting Posture Analysis in Material Handling Using Virtual Humans|journal=Manufacturing Engineering and Materials Handling, Parts a and B|pages=1445\u20131453|publisher=ASMEDC|doi=10.1115/imece2005-81801|isbn=0-7918-4223-1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hariri|first=Mahdiar|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Chung|first3=Hyun-Joon|last4=Bhatt|first4=Rajan|last5=Arora|first5=Jasbir|last6=Abdel-Malek|first6=Karim|date=2013-10-21|title=Simulation and Prediction of the Motion of a Human in a Vertical Jumping Task|journal=Volume 1: Aerial Vehicles; Aerospace Control; Alternative Energy; Automotive Control Systems; Battery Systems; Beams and Flexible Structures; Biologically-Inspired Control and Its Applications; Bio-Medical and Bio-Mechanical Systems; Biomedical Robots and Rehab; Bipeds and Locomotion; Control Design Methods for Adv. Powertrain Systems and Components; Control of Adv. Combustion Engines, Building Energy Systems, Mechanical Systems; Control, Monitoring, and Energy Harvesting of Vibratory Systems|publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers|doi=10.1115/dscc2013-4091|isbn=978-0-7918-5612-3}}</ref>   Furthermore, the gradient based methodology used to solve for the motion was also replaced with an artificial intelligence neural network method.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bataineh|first=Mohammad|last2=Marler|first2=Timothy|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Arora|first4=Jasbir|date=April 2016|title=Neural network for dynamic human motion prediction|journal=Expert Systems with Applications|volume=48|pages=26\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.eswa.2015.11.020|issn=0957-4174|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bataineh|first=Mohammad|title=Artificial Neural Network-Based Prediction of Human Posture|date=2013|work=Digital Human Modeling and Applications in Health, Safety, Ergonomics, and Risk Management. Human Body Modeling and Ergonomics|pages=305\u2013313|publisher=Springer Berlin Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-642-39181-1|last2=Marler|first2=Timothy|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-39182-8_36}}</ref>\n\nThe mathematical model for the Santos skeleton was developed based on the [[Denavit\u2013Hartenberg parameters|Denavit-Hartenberg]] method for kinematic and dynamic analysis.<ref>Denavit, J., & Hartenberg, R. S. (1955). A kinematic notation for lower-pair mechanisms based on matrices. Journal of Applied Mechanics,\n77, 215\u2013221.</ref> Optimization is used to determine postures and motions that are governed by various human performance measures (objective functions) and constrained by the restrictions imposed by the skeleton, the laws of physics, and the environment. The Santos simulation platform is being used by the US Military, industry (for example automotive industry),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Kim|first2=Joo H.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Beck|first5=Steven|last6=Kopp|first6=Gregory R.|date=July 2007|title=A new digital human environment and assessment of vehicle interior design|journal=Computer-Aided Design|volume=39|issue=7|pages=548\u2013558|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2006.11.007|issn=0010-4485}}</ref> and academia.  The Virtual Soldier Research team transitioned a product from the Santos environment called Enhanced Technologies for the Optimization of Warfighter Load (ETOWL) funded by the Office of Naval Research (ONR) to the US Marines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://popularmilitary.com/gruntsim-the-marines-new-infantry-simulator/|title=GruntSim, the Marines' new infantry simulator|website=popularmilitary.com|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The product was later renamed as GruntSim.<ref>{{Citation|title=GruntSim is a US Marines simulation for lightening the load, warfighter load, Predictive Dynamic|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RC8hseUmZDw|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>   This human modeling and simulation environment is now being used to  study human factors<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Yu|first2=Wei|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=November 2004|title=A mathematical method for ergonomic-based design: placement|journal=International Journal of Industrial Ergonomics|volume=34|issue=5|pages=375\u2013394|doi=10.1016/j.ergon.2004.05.001|issn=0169-8141}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=DEPARTMENT OF THE ARMY WASHINGTON DC|date=1987-05-08|title=Administration: Civilian Aides to the Secretary of the Army|location=Fort Belvoir, VA|doi=10.21236/ada401816}}</ref> and ergonomics<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Mi|first3=Zan|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=2004-06-15|title=Layout Design using an Optimization-Based Human Energy Consumption Formulation|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2004-01-2175}}</ref> in many applications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Rahmatalla|first3=Salam|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Bhatt|first5=Rajankumar|last6=Abdel-Malek|first6=Karim|date=2010-01-21|title=Human lifting simulation using a multi-objective optimization approach|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=23|issue=4|pages=431\u2013451|doi=10.1007/s11044-009-9186-y|issn=1384-5640}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Arora|first4=Jasbir S.|last5=Abdel-Malek|first5=Karim|date=2010-03-31|title=Dynamic motion planning of overarm throw for\u00a0a\u00a0biped\u00a0human multibody system|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=24|issue=1|pages=1\u201324|doi=10.1007/s11044-010-9193-z|issn=1384-5640}}</ref>  This model includes not only Predictive Dynamics but also stability criteria called Zero Moment Point.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=J.H.|last2=Xiang|first2=Y.|last3=Bhatt|first3=R.M.|last4=Yang|first4=J.|last5=Chung|first5=H.-J.|last6=Arora|first6=J.S.|last7=Abdel-Malek|first7=K.|title=Generating Effective Whole-Body Motions of a Human-Like Mechanism with Efficient ZMP Formulation|date=2009|journal=International Journal of Robotics and Automation|volume=24|issue=2|doi=10.2316/journal.206.2009.2.206-3235|issn=1925-7090}}</ref>  The use of the Santos Digital Human Model for example in assessing assembly issues in the design stage have been demonstrated<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Pitarch|first2=Esteban Pena|last3=Kim|first3=Joo|last4=Abdel-Malek|first4=Karim|date=2006-07-04|title=Posture Prediction and Force/Torque Analysis for Human Hands|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2006-01-2326}}</ref> and for gait prediction as well.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Hyung Joo|last2=Horn|first2=Emily|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir S.|last4=Malek|first4=Karim Abdel-|date=2005-06-14|title=An Optimization-Based Methodology to Predict Digital Human Gait Motion|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2710}}</ref>  Running for example,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Qian|last2=Xiang|first2=Yu-Jiang|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir|last4=Abdel- Malek|first4=Karim|date=2007-04-23|title=Alternative Formulations for Optimization-Based Human Gait Planning|journal=48th AIAA/ASME/ASCE/AHS/ASC Structures, Structural Dynamics, and Materials Conference|location=Reston, Virigina|publisher=American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics|doi=10.2514/6.2007-1909|isbn=978-1-62410-013-0}}</ref> which substantially more difficult to predict for a virtual human, was accomplished.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hyun-Joon|last2=Xiang|first2=Yujiang|last3=Mathai|first3=Anith|last4=Rahmatalla|first4=Salam|last5=Kim|first5=Joo|last6=Marler|first6=Timothy|last7=Beck|first7=Steve|last8=Yang|first8=Jingzhou|last9=Arora|first9=Jasbir|last10=Abdel-Malek|first10=Karim|last11=Obusek|first11=John|date=2007-06-12|title=A Robust Formulation for Prediction of Human Running|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2007-01-2490}}</ref>\n\nThe Santos simulation platform was developed from the ground up.  Using the 215 DOF and based on the use of optimization based methods that enable cost functions to drive the motion, the numerical algorithm drives the motion to predict joint variables across time (also called joint profiles) and subject to a number of constraints.  For example, predicting gait of any body type is now possible.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=April 2011|title=Erratum to \"Optimization-based prediction of asymmetric human gait\" [J. Biomech. 44 (4) (2011) 683\u2013693]|journal=Journal of Biomechanics|volume=44|issue=6|pages=1217|doi=10.1016/j.jbiomech.2011.02.080|issn=0021-9290}}</ref>  Similarly, any task can be modeled and simulated using this approach.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Malek|first2=Karim Abdel|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Marler|first4=R. Timothy|date=2006|title=Prediction and analysis of human motion dynamics performing various tasks|journal=International Journal of Human Factors Modelling and Simulation|volume=1|issue=1|pages=69|doi=10.1504/ijhfms.2006.011683|issn=1742-5549}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2008-05-14|title=Optimization-based motion prediction of mechanical systems: sensitivity analysis|journal=Structural and Multidisciplinary Optimization|volume=37|issue=6|pages=595\u2013608|doi=10.1007/s00158-008-0247-2|issn=1615-147X}}</ref> Xiang, Yujiang, Jasbir S. Arora, and Karim Abdel-Malek. \"Hybrid predictive dynamics: a new approach to simulate human motion.\" ''Multibody System Dynamics'' 28.3 (2012): 199-224.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiang|first=Yujiang|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir S.|last3=Abdel-Malek|first3=Karim|date=2012-03-28|title=Hybrid predictive dynamics: a new approach to simulate human motion|journal=Multibody System Dynamics|volume=28|issue=3|pages=199\u2013224|doi=10.1007/s11044-012-9306-y|issn=1384-5640}}</ref>\n\nThe Santos system was also used to predict injury for various activities, particularly musculoskeletal injuries in atheltics, military, manufacturing, and other domains.<ref>{{Citation|last=Sultan|first=Sultan|title=An Integrated Computational Simulation System for Injury Assessment|date=2016-07-06|work=Advances in Intelligent Systems and Computing|pages=23\u201334|publisher=Springer International Publishing|isbn=978-3-319-41626-7|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Arora|first3=Jasbir|last4=Bhatt|first4=Rajan|last5=Marler|first5=Tim|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-41627-4_3}}</ref>\n\nVSR research has led to the spin-off of a private company, Santos Human Inc.,<ref>http://www.santoshumaninc.com/</ref> specifically focused on product development.\n\n'''Who is Santos\u2122?'''\n\nSantos is the only physics-based<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Beck|first5=Steve|last6=Swan|first6=Colby|last7=Frey-Law|first7=Laura|last8=Mathai|first8=Anith|last9=Murphy|first9=Chris|last10=Rahmatallah|first10=Salam|last11=Patrick|first11=Amos|date=October 2006|title=Santos: A Physics-Based Digital Human Simulation Environment|journal=Proceedings of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society Annual Meeting|volume=50|issue=20|pages=2279\u20132283|doi=10.1177/154193120605002009|issn=1541-9312}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Malek|first=Karim Abdel|last2=Arora|first2=Jasbir|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou (James)|last4=Marler|first4=Timothy|last5=Beck|first5=Steve|last6=Swan|first6=Colby|last7=Law|first7=Laura Frey|last8=Kim|first8=Joo|last9=Bhatt|first9=Rajan|last10=Mathai|first10=Anith|last11=Murphy|first11=Chris|date=2009|title=A physics-based digital human model|journal=International Journal of Vehicle Design|volume=51|issue=3/4|pages=324|doi=10.1504/ijvd.2009.027960|issn=0143-3369}}</ref> virtual human that stands at the center of the digital human modeling and simulation research at the University of Iowa and in use by the US Army and the US Marines. This high-fidelity, biofidelic, biomechanically and physiologically accurate musculoskeletal model was developed from the inside out by a large multidisciplinary team, and incorporates 215 degrees of freedom, including the hand, feet, and eyes. The dimensions of the skeleton are mutable, able to represent any anthropometric cross section. In addition, Santos includes a muscular system with the ability to predict muscle activation and muscle forces in real time, using a novel optimization-based methodology.  The Santos system has been used in many applications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abdel-Malek|first=Karim|date=July 2007|title=Human modeling and applications special issue|journal=Computer-Aided Design|volume=39|issue=7|pages=539|doi=10.1016/j.cad.2007.04.001|issn=0010-4485}}</ref>\n\nOver time, the Santos family has grown to incorporate a variety of different body scans to provide a range of models that include our female version, Sophia, and a broad array of different body shapes, types, and sizes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Marler|first2=Tim|last3=Kim|first3=HyungJoo|last4=Farrell|first4=Kimberly|last5=Mathai|first5=Anith|last6=Beck|first6=Steven|last7=Abdel-Malek|first7=Karim|last8=Arora|first8=Jasbir|last9=Nebel|first9=Kyle|date=2005-04-11|title=Santos\u2122: A New Generation of Virtual Humans|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-1407}}</ref> Our research is currently being extended to allow multiple digital human models to interact with each other to complete tasks cooperatively.\n\nSantos was built using state-of-the-art technologies adapted from robotics, Hollywood, and the game industry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Jingzhou|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Farrell|first3=Kim|last4=Nebel|first4=Kyle|date=2004-01-01|title=The Iowa Interactive Digital-Human Virtual Environment|journal=Manufacturing Engineering and Materials Handling Engineering|pages=1059\u20131067|publisher=ASMEDC|doi=10.1115/imece2004-61791|isbn=0-7918-4713-6}}</ref> VSR research continues to grow in its dynamic capabilities, physiology, and intelligent behaviors through integration of Artificial Intelligence, design optimization, physics-based modeling, and advanced, multi-scale physiological models.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Joo H.|last2=Abdel-Malek|first2=Karim|last3=Yang|first3=Jingzhou|last4=Farrell|first4=Kimberly|last5=Nebel|first5=Kyle|date=2005-06-14|title=Optimization-Based Dynamic Motion Simulation and Energy Expenditure Prediction for a Digital Human|journal=SAE Technical Paper Series|volume=1|location=400 Commonwealth Drive, Warrendale, PA, United States|publisher=SAE International|doi=10.4271/2005-01-2717}}</ref>\n\nThe mathematical model for the Santos skeleton was developed based on the Denavit-Hartenberg method for kinematic and dynamic analysis. Optimization is used to determine postures and motions that are governed by various human performance measures (objective functions) and constrained by the restrictions imposed by the skeleton, the laws of physics, and the environment. The software must be as fast and efficient as possible in an effort to provide real-time simulations.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n<!-- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n[[Category:Anatomical simulation]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Iowa]]\n", "name_user": "Trappist the monk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:remove 'invisible' characters from cs1|2 template parameters; (3\u00d7 NBSP)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_Soldier_Research_Program"}
